      "question": "If $\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta = p$, show that $\\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1} = \\sin \\theta$.",
      "answer": "$\\sin \\theta$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Substitute $p = \\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta$ into the expression $\\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1}$.",
          "Expand the numerator using $(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)^2 - 1$.",
          "Apply the identity $\\sec^2 \\theta - 1 = \\tan^2 \\theta$ in the numerator.",
          "Expand the denominator using $(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)^2 + 1 = \\sec^2 \\theta + \\tan^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta + 1$.",
          "Use $1 + \\tan^2 \\theta = \\sec^2 \\theta$ to simplify the denominator.",
          "Cancel common terms to arrive at $\\sin \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "p^2 - 1 = (\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)^2 - 1 = \\sec^2 \\theta + \\tan^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta - 1 = (\\sec^2 \\theta - 1) + \\tan^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta = 2 \\tan^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta = 2 \\tan \\theta(\\tan \\theta + \\sec \\theta). \\\\ p^2 + 1 = (\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)^2 + 1 = \\sec^2 \\theta + \\tan^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta + 1 = \\sec^2 \\theta + (\\tan^2 \\theta + 1) + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta = 2 \\sec^2 \\theta + 2 \\sec \\theta \\tan \\theta = 2 \\sec \\theta(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta). \\\\ \\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1} = \\frac{2 \\tan \\theta(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)}{2 \\sec \\theta(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)} = \\frac{\\tan \\theta}{\\sec \\theta} = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} \\cdot \\cos \\theta = \\sin \\theta"
      },
